  "text": "Because treatment delay is a significant factor for mortality in patients with mycobacterial peritonitis [CITATION_1] , an early diagnosis is important. However, the early diagnosis of mycobacterial peritonitis in PD patients is very difficult because the symptoms and signs are indistinguishable from other bacterial peritonitis (4). The International Society for Peritoneal Dialysis guidelines emphasize that, in culture-negative peritonitis cases where empiric antibacterial therapy has failed, physicians should actively evaluate the peritoneal fluid for uncommon pathogens such as mycobacteria, fungi, and Nocardia [CITATION_2] . The diagnosis of PD-related peritonitis in the present case was based on the examination of an acidfast smear and culture.",
